TileMatrixSet.Abstract: This well-known scale set has been defined for global cartographic products. Rounded scales have been chosen for intuitive cartographic representation of vector data. Scale denominator is only accurate near the equator. Reference: https://www.opengeospatial.org/standards/wmts Version 1.0.0, Page 102. Normal Tile size is 256 x 256 pixels.

This well-known scale set has been defined for global cartographic products. Rounded pixel sizes have been chosen for intuitive cartographic representation of raster data. Some values have been chosen to coincide with original pixel size of commonly used global products like STRM (1" and 3"), GTOPO (30") or ETOPO (2' and 5'). Scale denominator and approximated pixel size in meters are only accurate near the equator. Reference: https://www.opengeospatial.org/standards/wmts Version 1.0.0, Page 103. Normal tile size for NRL implementation is 256 x 256 pixels.

This well-known scale set has been defined to allow quadtree pyramids in CRS84. Level 0 allows representing the whole world in a single 256x256 pixels (where the first 64 and last 64 lines of the tile are left blank). The next level represents the whole world in 2x2 tiles of 256x256 pixels and so on in powers of 2. Scale denominator is only accurate near the equator. Reference: https://www.opengeospatial.org/standards/wmts Version 1.0.0, Page 104

This well-known scale set has been defined to be compatible with Google Maps and Microsoft Live Map projections and zoom levels. Level 0 allows representing the whole world in a single 256x256 pixels. The next level represents the whole world in 2x2 tiles of 256x256 pixels and so on in powers of 2. Scale denominator is only accurate near the equator. Reference: https://www.opengeospatial.org/standards/wmts Version 1.0.0, Page 105

A default WGS84 tile matrix set where the second zoom level (labeled zoom level 1) covers the world with two tiles on the horizonal axis and one tile over the vertical axis and each subsequent zoom level is calculated by half the resolution of its previous zoom level; first zoom level is the entire world covered in a single tile. From NRL's own standard. Normal Tiles are 512 x 512 pixels.
A default WGS84 tile matrix set that is the same as NRLTileScheme, only with 256 x 256 pixel tiles. From NRL's own standard.

The scale levels are calculated based on the tile size (256 by 256) and the WGS 1984 Web Mercator Auxiliary Sphere coordinate system, such that when tiles are laid out starting at 180W and proceeding eastward, the final tile aligns perfectly (no overlap) with the first tile at the international date line. Reference: https://doc.arcgis.com/en/data-appliance/6.4/reference/common-attributes.htm
